    "job_description": "\nMinimum Qualifications\nNon-Competitive: bachelor’s degree and five years of professional research experience in an appropriate field. –\n\n\n\n\nSubstitutions: master’s degree in an appropriate field may substitute for one year of experience, and Ph.D. in an appropriate field may substitute for an additional year of experience.\n\n\n\n\nExamples of acceptable degree fields are Epidemiology, Sociology, Biostatistics, Public Health, Biology, Psychology, Mental Health Counseling, Health Administration, Addiction Studies, Education, Human Services and other related field.\n\n\n\n\nPreferred Qualifications\nMaster’s or Doctoral degree in epidemiology, public health, public policy, statistics/biostatistics, public administration, or closely related fieldIntermediate or advanced knowledge of SAS, geographical information systems (GIS) and TableauAt least 2 years’ experience integrating health equity principles into surveillance, epidemiology and research At least 2 years’ experience analyzing population-based survey data At least 2 years’ experience in chronic disease surveillance, epidemiology or research At least 2 years’ experience with supervision of research and data analysis staff\nDuties Description\nThe Research Scientist 4 is responsible for providing support to the Bureau of Research and Program Evaluation, and for working directly with the Bureau Director in the evaluation of multiple initiatives supported by state and federal funding opportunities managed by DMRP. Initiatives are designed to develop and enhance prevention, harm reduction, treatment and recovery services throughout the state.\n\n\n\n\nCandidates must have technical data management and analysis expertise using public health and administrative health service data. The successful candidate will demonstrate experience leading and collaborating in the conduct of program evaluations and analytic projects for inclusion in dissemination and professional materials. Ability to calculate, interpret and communicate statistics from data systems and provide findings in a variety of formats to both technical and general audiences. Proficiency in SAS, R, and Microsoft programs Excel, Word, Access, and PowerPoint is required.\n\n\n\n\nResponsibilities Include, But Are Not Limited To\nConduct analyses of real-time OASAS program data and create data visualizations of program evaluation metrics and program data Format, clean, and manage administrative data including merging multiple data sources with OASAS program data for analyses and program evaluation Serve as a survey and data management liaison to support program initiatives Contribute to the execution of evaluation projects that address OASAS and Division initiatives and program implementation Contribute to the execution of research projects that result in publishable contributions that answer important questions in the addictions field, inform policy and open avenues for further study Work collaboratively with various OASAS divisional projects under the direction of the Bureau Director Support the development of policies and procedures to support Bureau functions Edit written reports, presentations, and other work products developed by the Bureau Anticipate Bureau needs particularly with respect to data analyses and data products Provide timely, professional, and accurate data products to the Bureau Director including providing data products on short timeframes Supervise junior staff Other duties as assigned by Bureau Director\nAdditional Comments\n+3,087 location pay\n\n\n\n\nExcellent Health Insurance Benefits Including Vision and Dental, NYS Employees Retirement System (Pension), Optional Deferred Compensation, Continuing Education Benefits, Generous Paid Leave Benefits, Compensation for 12 State holidays per year.\n\n\n\n\nTelecommute may be discussed at interview\n\n\n\n\n",
